                <head>7. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On July 8, 1972, at Washington, Secretary of Commerce <persName
                        corresp="#p_PPG_1">Peter G. Peterson</persName>, U.S. Chairman of the
                    U.S.-Soviet Joint Commercial Commission; Secretary of Agriculture Earl L. Butz;
                    and M.R. Kuzmin, First Deputy Minister of Foreign Trade of the <gloss
                        target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss>, signed an agreement regarding Soviet grain
                    purchases in the United States. The three-year agreement provided for Soviet
                    purchases of a total of $750 million in U.S. grains, the largest Soviet purchase
                    of U.S. grain to date. (Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin,</hi>
                    July 31, 1972, pages 144–145)</p>
            </div>
